We recommended that the Local Chief Executive  direct the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Immediately cause the issuance of the necessary follow up Demand Letters to the persons responsible/liable for the liquidation of the ₱70,395.00 cash advances; 
b. Ensure submission of the liquidation reports and/or settlement of the same to the Office of the COA Auditor for review. The necessary documents must be attached to the liquidation reports, such as the official receipts, certificate of seminar/trainings completed, etc; 
c. Avoid the recurrence of similar lapses, introduce controls that would assure that cash advances are liquidated or reported as soon as the purpose of the cash advance is served, in compliance with Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular 97-002; and 
d. Strictly monitor the timely submission of liquidation reports and completeness of supporting documents in accordance with COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012. We likewise recommended, if warranted, the filing of charges against the persons liable in the proper Court for failure to produce the accountability upon demand in violation of Article 217 of the Revised Penal Code.

